The paper proposes a novel approach for user-cell association in wireless small cell networks, which involves designing utility functions based on context information extracted from users' devices. This approach aims to improve the quality of service (QoS) requirements for different applications used by the users. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category. Additionally, the paper involves formulating a matching game between small cell base stations (SBSs) and user equipments (UEs), which requires designing interdependent preferences. This aspect of the paper is likely to be relevant to the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) categories. Furthermore, the paper proposes a distributed algorithm for self-organizing stable matching, which involves using context-aware features to improve QoS. This aspect of the paper is likely to be relevant to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) categories.
